# 🧠 Key Takeaways

* Always validate “legitimate-looking” binaries like updates
* Base64 & obfuscation are common in malware delivery
* PowerShell is heavily abused for fileless execution
* Browser-based payload delivery is rising (JS fetch abuse)
* Static + behavioral correlation is critical in SOC work

---

# 🏁 Conclusion

This challenge demonstrates how a seemingly harmless updater can:

* Hide malicious URLs
* Use encoded payload delivery
* Execute remote binaries silently
* Trigger multiple alerts across systems

A proper SOC analyst must:

* Extract IOCs quickly
* Correlate across alerts
* Understand attacker techniques

